Flying out this afternoon...

column3: West Canada Lakes, Cedar Lakes, Pillsbury, Lost Pond, French Louie's Fireplace, Brooktrout Lake
column5: Very taxing run. Lots of blowdown and route finding especially on Lost Pond Trail. No mud to speak of but lots of blowdown and undergrowth. Beautiful loop, enjoyed it a lot. Great scenery... Left Myka home for this one as water sources were scarce for long sections and it was hot, so I was worried about her...

column3: Some Things can't be Explained, Felt Great
column5: 93 mile week on 4 runs, 51 on the weekend back to back. Thought today's run would be torture but I felt great, especially at the end. No clue why but I'll take it... Happy Father's Day to all the Dads out there!
Trails are in good shape. Lakes: Pine, West, Nine Corner, Stewart, Indian and Otter. 2X over Kane Mountain. Ran out of daylight again.
Felt good, tried to do progression last half and finish strong.
Beautiful Day! Saw some Loons...

column3: Benson to Piseco- Actually 44.5 Miles- Battery Died at 38
column5: Bumming that Garmin battery quit. Very tough run, lots of hours. Trails had a lot of blowdown, going was slow. Many beautiful sights along this section of Northville Placid Trail. Did this with Myka and John Geesler. Myka is tired but did well. I'm tired too but will try to get up to run with Paul in the morning.

column3: Ready for a Rest Day- 106 Miles this Week on Four Runs

Ran with John and Myka, nice easy pace.

St. Johnsville to Schoharie Crossing/Ft. Hunter. Really didn't plan on 55 miles but during the run I realized that this would be my last chance to do 55 as a 55 Y.O. (birthday July 9) , so tacked on a little. Felt very strong at the end which was nice. Limited access to water refills so it made a hot day a little tougher. Glad to see the car! John Geesler talked me into this, need to find new friends. Haha
Felt good, leg cramps cleared up overnight.
Peaceful Run with pickup last 6 miles. Last mile 6:40. Garmin file corrupt, hopefully watch isn't junk. Ate some blackberries along the way.

Nice run with Paul, felt pretty good. Legs a little fatigued but overall pretty good...

Just making up for some of the Tuesday miles I lost. 26 for the day.
Enjoyed the evening... Looking forward to running long in the morning.

Totally unprepared for this. On my own, Myka stayed home to play with the grandkids so I had some flexibility. 5 slow on the trails, then some hills on roads. Tried to push up them. Pushed the downhills. Finished in the dark. Got through it with no fuel and didn't carry water. Stopped at a cemetery for a drink though. Had fun mixing it up...

Hilly 20 with Paul and Joe, felt spent a few times during this one.
3x1200, 2x400, 4x200. Felt pretty good overall considering this was the tail end of a high mileage week.
Tacked on a few easy miles to reach 100 for the week.
Pushed the last few miles. 126.5 running miles the past 7 days plus 15.5 walk miles. Hit 1100 miles for OneNY. It's been fun but I'm  kinda glad it's over!
Relaxing run and conversation...
I wasn't planning on working this but felt pretty good. Started losing focus miles 4 and 5 but was able to get focused again for the last mile. Weather was perfect...
Just a few miles, mini-taper for Boston Virtual Saturday. Not going all out for that, but would like to go into it with fresh legs.
Had a blast with my buddy Bill Callahan, perfect weather!
Trails are beautiful, covered with fallen leaves. Corn has been chopped in the fields. Myka put up a few flocks of geese, such a cattle dog..
Nice chilly morning- enjoyed the run with Paul and Doug.

column3: Falling Leaves Course plus a few
column5: Paul and I planned on doing the Falling Leaves course as a hard tempo, but my legs felt the marathon effort from last weekend. Thought I had done it without any after effects but no-such-luck, legs are a little sore so we just ran this pretty easy.
Enjoyed chatting with John Geesler.
5:22 official time.
Had a great time chatting it up! Really enjoyed the company. GPS file is a little screwed up, but ran 50K after Clint planted the seed..

column3: Nice Easy Stroll with Myka and John Geesler

column5: Pretty challenging doing Switchbacks X2, nice cruising on the downs but pretty challenging on the ups. Amazing how little of the course is flat, almost none.

Really happy to be able to run this with Paul. Hats off to him for pulling this together and running it with less than a week's notice! Great that Mike, Joe and Doug were able to make it for some or all of the miles. I really enjoyed the run and the company.
Well, I walked anyway, the dog ran 100 MPH most of the time.

column3: Trail 20- Cold Feet with Myka, Perfect Fall Weather!
column5: Was supposed to be a ~16 mile loop, but I started second guessing myself. I wasn't 100% sure on a few intersections so instead of going further I turned back at 10 miles since I had no food or water. Turns out I should have pressed on and completed the loop. Beautiful views from Good Luck Cliffs, fall colors are stunning.

column3: Last Tuesday Trail Run until Spring
column5: Once clocks change this weekend it'll be dark too early for this.

column3: Depositing Pennies to Empire Race-Off Piggy Bank
column5: Wanted to make this into a 20 but Myka got antsy trying to figure out why we were running in circles for 16 miles. Cattle dogs just don't know what fun is I guess. Haha. I'll try to get out for 4-5 later today and hopefully 20 or so tomorrow.

column3: More Pennies for the Race-Off Piggy Bank #finalpush
column5: Ran the first 14 with Paul. Planned on up to 26 mile distance but decided to add on.  Tried to do progression in the later miles, felt good the whole run.
A few more to add to Empire Race-Off, hopefully URR can finish 2nd place team. Very exciting final day for the teams toggling between 2nd and 3rd place on the final day!

column3: Deerfield Town Park XC Trails with Paul

Had a blast with Cory, Joe and Clint!!

Other than the last 10k or so, I just ran with Tom, Joe, Jonathan and Michael for the most part. Really happy that we got a group together for this. I owe you guys big-time. Windy today and had to stop for water so splits are pretty inconsistent. Thanks Rob for manning the water stops!
Felt pretty good for this one.

column3: Thanksgiving Walk with the Cattle Dog

column5: Still feel the marathon in my legs, hopefully by next week it will be worked out!

column3: Cattle Dog #2 Walk- Additional Family Member
column5: Couldn't pass up Tyson, he was at Herkimer Humane Society. 10 month old Australian Cattle dog. He had too much energy for the previous owners. Myka needed a playmate, hopefully it works out.
Myka and Tyson are getting along pretty well... Beautiful day for a hike.

column3: Bushwhack Nine Corner Lake with Myka and Tyson
column5: Myka and Tyson did well, starting to bond. They had a blast, so much fun to watch them play and interact. Hopefully they can do some 50+ mile trail runs next summer.
Nice 20 with Joe, Rob and Dan. Great to get a long run with Rob after not running with him for quite a few years!

column3: North Branch Hike with the Dogs
column5: Nice day for a hike, a few inches of snow on the ground.
Had fun with my Grandson and the puppies...
Got to say hello to Tim Kane in his stomping grounds. Great run with Joe and Paul...
Chilly but not too bad since there was only a slight breeze. Nice of Joe to invite us for this. Good to run with Joe, Clint E. and Jonathan.

Absolutely beautiful run, ice on the trees around the lake was stunning. Great run with Nate, Clint and Aaron. Lots of good conversation. I was telling them a childhood story and Nate says "Dave, you should talk with someone about this". I said "yeah, I know, that's what I'm doing now"  :-).  Thanks guys for the invite, really enjoyed it!
Nice to see Farb, haven't run with him in a while. Paul and I talked him into a few extra miles so I could get to 2500 for the year. I don't think he was too mad at us.

Nice chilly start. Warmed up as the sun came up! Good to catch up with Paul and Doug after taking some time off from running.

column3: Broomstick Lake Hike with the Dogs
column5: Short but beautiful...
Just enough snow, ice on the trees was beautiful with the sun shining through them!

column3: Nice Walk with the Dogs, but should have Ran
column5: Hard packed, would have been nice for running.

column3: Broomstick Lake with my Grandson and the Dogs.
column5: Hiked up the creek and found some well formed ice pods.
Footing was not great, snowed most of the run. Snow was very pretty. It was great to run with Paul, Joe, Bill and Doug.

column3: 10K Snowmobile Trail Hike with the Dogs
column5: Pretty with all the fresh snow. Dogs wanted to chase the snowmobiles but they're learning...

column3: Slippery, some Wind and a bit Chilly
column5: Nice run with Doug, glad we got out. Suneed met us at 14 miles which was awesome for the final 8 miles or so. Wasn't as cold as expected, footing wasn't very good..

column3: Snowmobile Trail Skiing- cold to start
column5: Nice ski with Geez and Bart. Third Lake had quite a bit of slush and water under a layer of snow, so we took the trail on the way back.

column3: Nine Corner with the Dogs and Grandson

column5: Really enjoyed this one with the guys, miles flew by. Thanks to Clint for the hospitality..  As others have said on Strava, it was nice to have dry pavement to run on. It has been a few weeks running on snow, ice and slush!

column3: Irving Pond and Bellows Lake Ski
column5: Cold, John's truck thermometer said -10 at the start. Dogs seemed like their feet were cold for a while. They chased a few snowmobiles, really trying to get them to ignore the snowmobiles. They are getting better, but I think their herding instinct gets in the way of teaching them.
Snow just stuck to skis, so decided to abort this mission...
#Elevationmap

Cold to start (my weather station showed -6 temp, -15 wind chill), the sun and climbing helped warm us up. Hit a snowmobile trail for about 1 1/2 miles. Ran over to the base of a windmill tower... Fun run, miles clicked off pretty quickly it seemed.. glad Joe came over for this.

Great running with Paul, Doug and Mr. Callahan. First 16 with the whole group then added on with Bill so we both got to 60 for the week. It's been a while for me, mileage has been low due to skiing and hiking...
Very windy tonight, roads glassed over with ice...
Joe mapped out a great course, challenging.. especially the last mile. Really enjoyed the run and chatting with Joe. Good footing today .

column3: Teaching Christopher to ski down hills
column5: He had to take a few dives on the steep downs but did really well for his first real hills. Had a blast...

column3: Beautiful Morning, we even got to see the Sun!!
column5: Nice run with Paul and Doug, it was a little cold at the start but warmed up...

column3: Nice Leisurely Stroll with John and Jason

column5: Fun run with Clint and Joe. Really got warm today... Went off road to the summit of Barto Hill to catch the 360 degree view. Snowmobile trail up, then bushwhack down to Castle Road. Slow mile but fun...  Clint had a few battle wounds from the combination of blackberry bushes and shorts.  #elevationmap

column3: Short Hatch Loop plus an add-on
column5: Thanks Clint for putting this together. Great to run with Paul, Clint, Joe and Doug. Mix of Ice/snow/slop. Some snow then sleet...

column3: Ski Stewarts Landing to Caroga Lake

Planned on 14 with Paul, but decided to add on to get to 20. Felt good so decided to add on a few more. Felt good the whole run.

column3: Dexter Lake and Waters Mills Pond Ski
column5: Icy and fast today!
Great run with Clint and Joe. Perfect weather and a great course!!

Nice to get out with Paul, Bill and Doug.. nice to run on sidewalks and shoulders without snow. I had no reason to trip, but somehow my toe caught something on the sidewalk and I fell forward. Not much hurt but I felt silly falling on a bare sidewalk. Luckily my head broke my fall.
Tagged along with Rob for a tempo workout. Mine was 3X 1.5 Miles @ ~6:20-6:30 pace. Felt good to get the legs moving a little faster...

column3: Nice to see the Canal Trail!

column5: Had a blast with Cory, Joe, Clint and Doug! Amazing that everyone held up well for this challenging trail run. A little muddy and ice here and there but that made it more fun.
I've wanted to get in a few 40 mile weekends, but Sunday skiing interferes with that plan. Getting 26 with the superstars yesterday got me close enough to get a little over 40.

column3: Tuesday from Hu-Hill Farm, Ft. Plain
column5: Nice Tuesday run from Rob Hudyncia's farm with the Tuesday group..

column3: Birthday Run with the 42 Year Olds
Sightseeing and Trails in Little Falls
column5: Nice recovery run..

Screwed up my watch at the start, so I fiddled around with it for the first .2 miles and got it going. Then I had to learn how to race again, it's been so long since live racing. It was great to see everyone out there. Wow were there some fast runners! Thanks to the Roman Runners for making this event happen!!!  Felt good today, was able to negative split each mile, probably just because I was able to relax as the race progressed.

column3: Kane, Nine Corner, Stewart and Indian Lakes
column5: Nice Tuesday trail run with Geez and Paul.

Awesome course that Doug had run over the winter. Nice mix of hills and seasonal roads. Great conversations with Doug, Tom and Joe. Lots of laughs. Really enjoyed this run, thanks Doug for scouting it out!

column3: Whitehouse Suspension Bridge and Mud Lake
column5: Great run with Geez (AKA Uncle John) and niece Jen. In typical Geesler fashion, Jen went from a long run of 14 miles to 21 and had no trouble.  We even found a canoe at Mud Lake and paddled out to see the loons. Got pretty close to one of them. It was a blast.

column3: Little Falls Tuesday with some Trails
Cold Feet!! Snow and Wet Trails- Piseco to Spruce
column5: 23 degrees to start and windy. There was about 1/2" of snow and a lot of water so the snow stuck to sneakers. Warmed up for about the last 10 miles once the sun came out. Nice run with John Geesler and niece Jen. Also saw Paul Cirillo out on the trail!  I added on to get to long distance as a virtual run with Doug since our schedules didn't work out for his 10th consecutive weekly marathon. Congratulations Doug!

Fun run with Geez, Joe and Clint. It was great that Joe and Clint could make it down for some trails. The conversation we had after the run with Geez should have been recorded. I'd love to play it back as a reminder to never run for 6 or 10 days. Bad things happen.
Nice morning! Luckily Doug had some time this morning to run. Trail was beautiful, relaxing and dry considering the weather we've had!
Great weather today!!

column3: 6 Day Race Stories with John Geesler
column5: Fun to spend time with John after his 6 day race. He always comes back with some good stories.

column3: Piseco to Canada Lakes with John Geesler, Myka and Tyson
column5: Ended up being a beautiful day. Tyson's first ultra distance run. Trails in good shape. John worked out the kinks from his six day race. Saw a few moose tracks. Turned around at French Louie's Fireplace.

Luckily Clint spotted a huge fallen tree big enough for all 5 of us to hunker down under during the worst of it. That was 2:04 AM. Ended up making it to Mud Lake Lean-to at daybreak. Took a short rest before the return trip. We were blessed with a huge snapping turtle with a very shiny polished looking shell. Thought it was dead but it was very much alive. Near Woods Lake, Clint spotted two very small bear cubs. They climbed a huge tree, it was awesome. Joe and I lingered back for a few minutes and got to see the mother. She walked out and gave us a stern stare as if to say "get the eff out of here". We did. The last 10 miles seemed like it took forever. I think we all had sore feet from being wet for over 20 hours. All in all, a very successful and fun trip!

column3: Scary Bear Encounter Mile 14- Myka and Tyson saved the day??
column5:
Great trail run with the Cattle Dogs, a lot of lakes- Ayers, Long, Third, Good Luck, Dry, Dexter lakes and Waters Millpond.  Even took a boat ride on Third Lake. There was a boat and makeshift paddle made of a branch and some duct tape. Myka was annoying trying to bite the paddle each time I switched sides. 
All was well until mile 14. Got to Good Luck trail register and turned toward Dry Lake.  Came over a little hill and saw 4 bears on/around the trail in a group, very close to us. They saw us and scattered, Three of them went to the right- the dogs followed those three. The 4th went to the left by itself... I was a little uncomfortable but have never been scared of any animal in the woods... well, that changed today. I called Myka and Tyson several times, I couldn't see or hear them. After calling them a few times, the bear that went to the left came back in a hurry. The bear jumped up on a large fallen tree trunk and stood up and stared at me. I didn't know what to do other than make myself look big. It was close enough that I could see its eyes. I put my arms out to look big and we just stared at each other. It seemed like we were staring at each other for a very long time (probably 20-30 seconds but it seemed like minutes!)... I didn't know what to do. I didn't want to yell to the dogs again and for sure didn't want to run, so I just stood there with my arms out staring, trying not to move. Luckily the dogs came running back. When they saw the bear, they went over to it but didn't bark or growl which I thought they would. Luckily they got close and the bear backed down, jumped off the log and ran a short distance. The dogs followed it, I was calling the dogs back, all the while looking behind me nervous that the other 3 bears were still around somewhere. The dogs started coming back and the bear turned at them, charged a short distance and made an odd hissing noise. Finally it turned away and kept going the other way and the dogs and I started going down the trail. It really freaked me out but I was glad the dogs were there. I've seen bears quite a few times in the woods, but never have I been nervous at all. Today I was scared shitless for a bit.  Really sorry for the long read but I don't know how to shorten it up (for anyone that actually read the whole thing). 
Oh and the thing that really struck me about the whole encounter was how quiet things were. I thought the dogs would be barking and growling. The only noise the whole time was me yelling at the dogs to come back and the hissing noise the bear made.

column5:
Tyson's journey began in Kentucky, where he was surrendered to a high kill shelter. We don't know anything more than that about his first 11 months of life. He (luckily) was transported to the Herkimer Humane Society, which is where we found him and fell in love with him. Myka needed a playmate! He definitely had (and still has) some baggage, but he's come a long way since we adopted him as a family member. If you are bored and wish to continue reading, the following poem fits Tyson 100 percent!

Now that I'm home, bathed, settled and fed,
All nicely tucked in my warm new bed,
I'd like to open my baggage,
Lest I forget,
There is so much to carry,
So much to regret.

Hmmm...Yes, there it is, right on the top,

Let's unpack Loneliness, Heartache and Loss,
And there by my leash hides Fear and Shame.

As I look on these things I tried so hard to leave,
I still have to unpack my baggage called Pain.

I loved them, the others, the ones who left me,
But I wasn't good enough - for they didn't want me.

Will you add to my baggage?
Will you help me unpack?

Or will you just look at my things,
And take me right back?
Do you have the time to help me unpack?

To put away my baggage, to never repack?
I pray that you do - I'm so tired you see,
But I do come with baggage,
Will you still want me?

By Evelyn Colbath

column5:
Was going to go short, but decided to extend, there are a few good water pipes along the route to get nice cold spring  water. 
Going through St. Johnsville I saw an elderly lady sitting on the curb with her door open and her cane and pocketbook next to her. She didn't look like she was in distress, so I went past her. Then I thought, well, that's an odd place to sit. 
I went back and asked her if she needed anything. She said "yes, could you please help me up, then I'll be okay". I helped her up. She had opened the door, backed up and caught her heel on the curb and fell backwards. 
I asked her if she was okay, were her hips okay. She replied "Well, luckily I have a big dupa!".
 I only know what a dupa is because I have some polish friends that translated for me years ago. LoL. 
All in all a good long run today.

column3: Hilly 20 with Joe - through Norway and Gray
column5: Great to have Joe to run this with. Miles clicked off quickly. Weather was great, muggy but not too hot.
Nate and I battled this out until the bitter end. We took 1st and 2nd. Fun. Flat as a pancake.

column3: Long Cool Down to the Amphitheater with Nate
column5: Nate took me on a nice sightseeing tour. It was awesome.

column3: Nice Long One with Chris and Nate
column5: Glad to have this week behind me. First time reaching a 100 mile week in a while, I think 105 ish. Felt pretty good. For the record, it was Nate's suggestion to hit the long distance on this run- and I'm usually pretty agreeable.
Glad Craig dragged me out for this one. This was my 25th 20+ miler in this Chicago Marathon training block. Getting close now.

Time to start winding it down for Chicago. Thanks Joe for mapping this out and running another long one with me. Started with Paul for the first 10. Nice cool morning for it, felt good, but legs definitely need a little lighter mileage and sharpening before Chicago.

column3: Recovery Miles with Paul, Tom and Joe
column5: Dark to start and a bit chilly! It was nice to do a short run, much needed!
Nice EZ 20 with Paul, PGXC race #1 tomorrow. Garmin seems to like the long runs as far as an endurance score. Hopefully it is a good sign going into the taper.
Fun race, great course with a whole bunch of fast and great people!!!
Hit some trails and did some strides with Paul. Nice enjoyable night!!
Good times with the Kickers! By lap 4 I was fading and Clint blew by. Chase went by with about 200 to go. Congratulations to Clint!
Freshly mowed and marked out. Beautiful conditions and a nice cool morning for it!

Great to run with Chris, Joe and Paul in this great weather. We all told a few marathon stories which was fun. Chris had the Idea. First 14 with everyone, Joe and I added on to get to 18. Last longer run before Chicago.
Great event, so much fun!
Shaking out Falling Leaves on Sandy Lane!
Messed up the first one, trying out the watch on autopilot. Couldn't get to a track so Paul and I did them on the canal path.
Nice easy run with Paul and Joe - Beautiful morning!

column3: Last Double Digit until the Marathon
column5: Nice to run with Jim Fiore and Jerry. It's been many years since we've run with Jim!
Very nice race, so much fun. There are so many good runners in this series, just a bunch of great people! Very happy with the effort, pretty hilly course. Last tune-up race for Chicago!
Nice to run with Craig before our marathons. Miles were faster than MP but felt good.

column3: Last Run- Fly to Chicago Tomorrow!
Chicago Marathon!!! Super Happy! Lifetime PR- Official Time 2:46:44
column5:
Huge thanks to everyone who helped me train and support me. Especially my family, training friends and everyone  in Strava Land. I can't put it in words how thankful I am to everyone. 
I decided to go for it, felt like a huge effort the whole way. My legs were starting to buckle the last 2 miles. I thought they were going to fail me, but they luckily got me to the finish. Nice surprise, [strava://athletes/36905005/8]Cat Beck and I finished almost the same time and saw each other at the finish line! Awesome! I have to look but I'm told I was 3rd USA and 12th World for the Abbott World Majors Age Group Championship!

Taking some deep breaths and trying to absorb the last few days. Chicago was such a rush- just a quick trip full of excitement. Abbott posted the top 3 Americans (55-59), I was happy to make that list. I'll probably take a short run tomorrow, feeling tired but all in all okay today. Feeling really happy to have the stress of the marathon behind me.
All systems go. Felt good- nice night with Craig, Rob and Rick. Got another invite from Abbott, have to decide whether to go to Sydney next year as a 60 year old.
Easing back into it. Feeling pretty good.

column3: Geese are Flying South, Frost on the Roofs and Long Pants
column5: Just keeping it going, nice morning to run some trails nice and easy.

Great event, kudos to URR for putting this on. So many happy kids participated in the kids runs and appeared to have a blast! I'm definitely still feeling the marathon in my legs, but happy to run the race!

This was a very nice course with a lot of hills and dirt roads. I was starting to get the post-marathon blues, this will help. I always need a goal to keep motivated. [strava://athletes/29197135/21]Joe Pill Man Mashaw - we will have to do this course sometime before the seasonal roads become snowmobile trails.
Nice morning, actually pretty warm and muggy! Beat the rain.
Great to see everyone out here on this drizzly day. Weather ended up being pretty good, comfortable day for a run!
Nice cool morning. Met up with Tim, Aaron, Joe and Brett for this nice peaceful run. Partridge Hill Road is such a beautiful place!
Nice run with John and Rick, dark now from start to finish.
Pretty wet, fun.
Turned the legs over a little for the last 3 miles. Felt pretty good, nice morning for a run!

column3: Veterans Day Run - hit 200,000 miles on the way over.
column5: Started with Paul, Jim and Jerry. Went with Jerry for a nice easy 16. Beautiful morning, a little chilly to start but perfect temps after we got warmed up. The CRV hit 200,000.
This went better than I thought it would. Happy with the effort. Our Syracuse Track Club Men's Vets won the series. I've met a ton of great people this season, it's been a blast!!!
Nice stroll tonight. We even picked up a new Tuesday night runner.

column3: "Don't Disappoint Ross Run"-  12 Mile Progression Run
column5: There you go [strava://athletes/12636951/19]Ross Kirschenheiter , thought about you each mile. I didn't want to disappoint you. LoL.

column3: Ten on the Trails for Tallahassee
column5: Hit some trails while the weather is good. These trails are what we dream of. Perfect. Of course I had to stop to pet dogs, there were a few dog walkers out today. I just can't help myself.

column3: Beautiful Saturday for a Group Run
column5: Started out with Jim, Jerry and Nate on a mission to do 17. Met up with Scott Humphrey and Piper, so we ran some miles together, enjoyed it!
Met up with Nate and Chris, then met up with Geoff and John for some miles. Weather was perfect!
Nice to run with Tom and Joe, it's been way too long!!
Just John and I tonight. The rest of the Little Falls crew don't know what they missed.
Glad to get this in, I needed to get the legs turning over.
Paul joined us a for the first few miles. Wind was a bit chilly! Enjoyed the run with Tim.
Nice to get in some miles with Joe before he goes to work.
Nice run with Joe and Chris. Joe did the first 10 and had to go to work. Chris and I reversed the loop for the last 10.
Nice snowy one with John, Rob, Paul and Steven. Threw in a few strides on the way back.

column3: More Walking with a bunch of Strides
column5: Pretty nice down here!!

column3: One more walk/run before heading back to NY
column5: Couldn't help myself, there was a segment around the inner loop. I'll have to see if  the CR  holds until I get back.
Nice night for a run. Good crew- John, Paul, Rick and Steven ran. Paul and I did a few strides.
Beautiful course!!

Tons of energy at this race, quite an event. I didn't run to my potential, but had fun. Felt okay for the first mile, but never settled in. It felt pretty hot out there! Quite a group here representing the Upstate NY area!!
Great to run with Paul and Tim.  Weather was perfect, hopefully all of the Tallahassee travelers make it home today before the weather changes!!
With Rob, John, Rick and Jason.
Nice one with Jerry, Joe and Nate. Joe tried very hard to keep us on course, but I made sure to disobey his orders and screw it up. We ended up okay with the distance regardless.

Great to run 20 with Clint, haven't run long with him for a while. Joe and I got in back to back 20's which was nice. Paul, Tim, Chris and Dan did 10 with us. Windy day, even in the city. Accidentally stopped my watch at 19 miles.
Chilly one this morning with Tim and Paul.
Happy with the effort. Started with Paul, Jerry and Chris, we all did different distances. I added on, hoping to get to 20 but felt good so I added on some more.
Nice easy one with Paul and Jason.
Pretty steady drizzle the whole run, but it sure is warm for late December! 13 with Tim and Paul, Joe and I added on to get to 20.
Great run with Aaron, Joe, Nate and Kevin. Kudos to Aaron and Kevin for stretching out the distance today. Pace was faster than we thought it would be.
Nice morning for a run. Paul ran with Nate and I for the first loop. Happy New Year!! Felt pretty good today.
We came across a small Raccoon on the trail, it wasn't afraid of us. Seemed like something was wrong with it.
Light snow most of the run. There was maybe an inch of fresh snow on the canal path, footing was pretty good. Very pretty along the canal! First 8 with Paul.
7 with Paul, 10 with Tim and 7 solo. Legs were tight early and then got tight again the last few miles. Felt pretty good overall, nice to hit some miles with Tim and Paul.

This was a difficult run for me, snowed the whole time and I never saw a snowplow. Footing was horrible going up the hills. Very pretty day, but it felt longer than 24 miles. 80 miles on 4 runs this week.

Huge group for this one! 11 of us started in the rain, it wasn't as windy as we thought it might be. Saw the sun for a few minutes around 13-15 miles in. Joe and I extended to get in a long distance. The weather turned bad on us for the last 4 miles or so. Very windy and rainy. Thanks Joe for putting this together and it was great to see so many hearty runners show up!!

First 10 with Paul. It was windy, but most of the headwind was on the downhills. Footing was good. Felt good today. Two gu's and one small Gatorade got me through and I was able to push the last few miles.

column3: Catching up with John Geesler post-6 Day
column5: Trotting along with John and Rick listening to good stories. He did 300 miles in 6 days with a very bad back. No sleep.
Joe's courses always hit hills. First 8 with Paul, Joe and I added on. Chilly and breezy, but good footing.
Nice to get this one in with Paul and Joe before it cools down tomorrow!

Fun run, really not as cold as I expected. It was great to have Josh, Sammy and Geoff come over to run with Paul, Joe and I. Great group, nice conversations. Joe said it's nice to have new people to tell our worn out stories to. LoL.  I was a little tired, stayed up past my bedtime at the STC Banquet. It was a really nice event! I really had a lot of fun running the PGXC series!
First 8 with Paul. I did a bunch of pickups, nothing structured. I just haven't been doing any races or speed work. It's a start anyway.

column3: 27 Miles plus one Sidewalk Barrel Roll- Also, heading to Sydney in September
column5: Great run with Paul, Chris and Tim. We all ran different distances. I was clumsy, tripped on a curb and fell on the sidewalk. No harm done, just felt foolish. Heading to Sydney for the Abbott World Age Group Championship in September. Looking forward to that, I'll be 60, doesn't seem possible!!!!
Garmin is whining again, I guess I'll lay low this coming week. Great group this morning - Paul, Chris, Ryan and Mike.

column3: Little Falls Tuesday - ATY Geesler Jacket showing
column5: John Geesler brought his jacket collection from the Across the Years races. He has 6 jackets from his years of running multi day races in Arizona. One jacket for every 1,000 miles he's completed. He earned his 6,000 mile jacket this year during his 6 day. He's  the only one with a 6,000 mile jacket. He also did the "around the clock" for 6 days, completing at least one lap (1.4 miles) during every hour for 6 days. 144 hours. Basically not sleeping...

column3: I can't believe it is February!
column5: 8 with Paul, 4 EZ add-on.
Fun!! That hill never gets any smaller!! Great to see everyone on such a beautiful day!!
Fun run with Paul, Chris and Mike. Plan was 10@MP during the 20 miler. My mind said "Yeah, let's do this!". Legs said "You're a really funny guy, we don't think so".
With Craig and Rick- nice evening for sure!

column3: 8 with Paul plus some Water Loop Repeats
column5: Added in 4 Water Loop Road loops. Just tried for hard on the up and quick on the down.

column3: Nice 20 with a Whole Bunch of Great People!

column5: Joe found some hills on this route. Paul was with Joe Mike and I for the first half. Great running weather!
Luckily, no wind and good footing. With Paul and Joe, last 5 Joe and I added on seemed to go by fast.
Very fun, Lake Effect loved up to its name! Great to see everyone, actually ended up having pretty good footing most of the time. It was great to see everyone !!
Sliding around with Paul, Joe, Josh K., Mike and Chris. Great  to see Josh, it's been a while.
First 8 with Paul and Mike, Joe and I added on the Tim Kane Loop to get to 20. Definitely hit some good hills on this route. Pickup at the end.

column3: 10 with Paul - a few Water Loop Repeats
column5: Did a 4 loops in Wolf speed. Missed one of the up hills, hit the pause instead of the lap button.
Chilly, but not as cold as we thought it would be. 10 with Tom, Chris, Mike and Sara. Sara, Mike and I went 20. Great course and a great group to run with!!
Happy with the effort, have to check results later. I didn't see any old people in front of me so hopefully I placed well. Going out for more miles now.

Legs definitely felt like I raced yesterday! First 10 with Chris, Sara and Joe. Paul and I added on to get in a long run. Definitely looking forward to a rest day tomorrow! Garmin has my endurance at an all time high, hopefully it is true going into Boston in 6 weeks!

column3: Started out Dark and Dreary, Sunny and Nice by the end
column5: Hoping to stack some 20's the next few days if all goes well.

Started with Paul and Joe, Joe and I continued on for a hilly 20. I knew I was in for it when I told Joe I ran on the canal yesterday. He responded "we won't be on the canal path today, Boston training today". He had a little smirk and twinkle in his eyes when he said it.
Another Hilly 20 courtesy of Tim Kane, great course. Great group of 10 for the first 13. Joe, Aaron and I went on to 20. Windy today, but temperature wasn't too bad. This was enjoyable.

column3: 20 #4- Day 4 of 4- Thanks Joe and Everyone
column5: Another great course and fun group. We ran into Josh B out on the run which was nice. Glad to have this week done. 90 miles for the week, and a bunch of Hilly 20's.

column3: Little Falls Tuesday - with 12x30 second Strides
column5: Fun Tuesday, thanks [strava://athletes/13616205/12]Paul Cirillo for pushing us to do the strides. Good way to mix it up.
Wow, that was painful. The mile is such a a rush for me, felt good for the first quarter mile. LOL. I owe [strava://athletes/32985877/14]Clint Eastwood a 6 Pack!

column3: More Marcy Hills- Feeling Mad Mile
column5: Joe mapped out the first 10, serious hills. My legs definitely felt yesterday's mile today. Felt better after the first 10 miles.

column3: Little Falls Tuesday - Trails and Sightseeing

column5: Nice run with Joe, Paul joined us for the first 7. Snowed pretty hard for a bit later in the run. We caught some heavy gusts of wind in the last few miles, but it wasn't bad going out on the canal path.
Not the best footing with race shoes!!! Happy with the effort, great to see a bunch of friends!!!!

This was my 33rd 20+ mile run in this training block. Thanks to all of my friends for the miles and company along the way. The training and friendships are the most rewarding part of running, hands down!! Thanks to Joe for running so many of them including today's run. Kind of a suffer fest for me with stomach and intestinal issues, but got it done.

Great course- Kudos to Tim for laying it out. Nice morning to run with Tim, Chris and Mike. Biggest aha moment was when we got to the "Water Loop" road sign. I said should we take the water loop Tim? Tim said no, we don't need it. Chris says "That's the Wafer Loop". I run over to the sign and look at it closely and said " that's why I should wear my contacts when I run, but I'll still call it the Water Loop". LoL.
Nice easy run with [strava://athletes/16321189/20]Irwin (Mike) Winkler , he hit a major milestone on this run, most weekly miles ever! Congratulations Mike!

column3: Little Falls Tuesday - Got Jason to 10 Miles

column5: Tom and Joe are going 45 miles for their birthday. I ran the first leg, Cory is running the last 17 with them. Good times with great friends!!

This is one of my favorite races, great course and great people to run and hang out with after the race. It was great talking with everyone after the race in the sun! Kudos to [strava://athletes/29987115/34]Matt (No More, okay fine...) Moore and the Roman Runners, such a great event, always so organized and well thought out!!

column3: 128th Boston Marathon - 7th AG 55-59- last one in my fifties
column5: I had hoped to go sub 2:50, but by 15k I was heating up. Pulled back a hair which I think was a good move. Great fun !! Great seeing everyone out there!!

That was more painful than I thought it would be, but got a little better the last few miles. Nice evening to run. Two weeks in a row for [strava://athletes/14074818/9]Joe Spohn which was nice. Other attendees were Rob, Marty and Rick. John wasn't there so we saved Sandy Lane for when he returns.
Nice and easy, Boston has mostly left my legs now, just minor fatigue, very little soreness.

A co-worker's uncle David from Australia was in town, he ran Boston and was here visiting family. He lives in Melbourne and will be running the Sydney Marathon, so we'll see him out there in September!! Great guy for sure!!  He's going to run the Big Sur Marathon on his way back to Australia in a few weeks.
Dave is leaving this morning, driving to Chicago then taking the train to California. Big Sur Marathon and back to Australia. We are definitely going to get together in Sydney!!

column3: Nice 6AM 10 miler with Chris and Joe
column5: A baby beaver was crouched next to the canal path, it was very much alive but didn't move. Hopefully it is okay.
I forgot my weight, so I couldn't get as deep or stay down as long as I wanted. Sorry in advance for the fish and turtle pictures. Visibility was pretty good this morning.
Storms seem to have broken a lot of the Elkhorn Coral- nice, but not what it was last time we were here.

column3: The Sunrise that wasn't, but found Money in the Desert
column5: Went out to catch the sunrise, but it was socked in with clouds. Still a nice hike, and we found little change on the ground .  The cactus picture is the only one we saw that had grown like that at the top.

column3: Tres Trapi, Boca Catalina, Malmok to Arashi.
column5: Visibility was a bit reduced today, but still pretty good. We still can't find an Octopus, we will keep looking!!
Trying to acclimate to the heat. 10k race Saturday at 5:30 PM, that should be interesting at 85 degrees!
I wish I could have gotten a little better photo, but it was moving a little faster than I could swim. I'd estimate 3-4' length.

column3: Mangel Halto- Excellent Visibility beyond the Break Wall
Malmok to Arashi Point to Point
column5: Took more time on this one trying to look very closely to find interesting creatures. We found a couple of small Eeels with some color.

column3: Alto Vista Chapel to Fisherman's Hut
62nd Harry Janseen International Boulevard Race- 10k Aruba- 10th Overall, 1st AG
column5: Wow, this was tough. 86 degrees!! Effort was 11 on a 1-10 scale. Ran my guts out. Met some really cool people, hopefully we will keep in touch. It was a pretty big event, 765 runners. It was a lot of fun hanging out after. I guess 38 minutes is a good time for this race because it's so hot, they made kind of a big deal about the old guy at the awards ceremony. It was a lot of fun. I even talked Beth into running it. She really enjoyed it as well!
One very large fish, got a picture from a distance. Need to identify it.  Edit: I think it is a Great Barracuda.

There's a break wall here that forms a channel along the ocean, it has a pretty good current. We found one eel, a large Pufferfish, and a school of very large Parrotfish. This was fun, very shallow and took a lot of navigating to get around the coral in the current.

Sorry, lots of pictures, we saw quite a bit on this one. Almost every time we go, we find a new creature that we haven't seen yet. Today I spotted a lobster. Not sure if they are the same as our lobsters in the cold Atlantic.
Hit some trails via Hoofs of Hope Farm. Headed up to the north point of the island, past California Lighthouse. Nice loop.

column3: Probably the last Adventure before heading home tomorrow
column5: The first two pictures are the same Flying Gunard. The cat (last picture) has become our friend!

column3: No More Fish!! Back in NY, 8 with Paul

column5: Marcy miles with Josh K., Chris and Paul. Lots of great conversations.

Great seeing everyone!!! Weather ended up being perfect, it sounded like it was going to be wet, but the rain held off. Mile 1 I felt okay, miles 2-7 I had stomach issues. Felt good again the last 3 miles.

column3: Stone Crusher Tour- Little Falls Tuesday
column5: Cool sightseeing in Little Falls. We took a less travelled trail over to the huge old stone crusher buildings. Very impressive, no one brought a camera though .
Felt good to get the legs moving a bit. Felt very clumsy the first few, it's been a while doing anything on the track. Nice to have the JFK track open!!
Beautiful morning, just a very slight and refreshing mist.
What an awesome group of runners! Great to see everyone, perfect racing conditions!

column3: Happy Mother's Day to all of you Stravaland Moms out there!!
column5: 10 Wet Miles with Tim, Paul and Josh K.!!
Nice and easy tonight!

column3: 59@59 Birthday Run!! Northville Placid Trail - Wakely to Benson Road
column5:
Thanks Tom, Joe, Paul and Sara (and Frankie  the pup) for making another birthday run happen!!! There was a ton of blowdown and mud, making the going very slow, especially during the night. We saw moose tracks early on, and one deer stood by the trail when we went by it during the night. It really was a blast!!! Weather was good, just a little bit of rain in the morning. Our feet are all pretty shot I think, hopefully they'll be better in a few days. 
I can't thank Tom and Joe enough for putting this together, all I have to do is show up!

column3: Little Falls Tuesday -  Big Group Tonight!
column5: I think there were 7 of us. Jake's first Tuesday. John was catching up with stuff at home after his 6 day so he didn't make it. Wink showed up. Good night to run, pretty warm!!

I've been hissed and honked at quite a few times when the geese are with their little ones along the canal. Today I went by a pair of them with 4 little ones, there was a fence on the left side and that's the side the geese were on. I slowed to a walk and went right as far as I could. One of them (as expected) turned and hissed. I walked slowly past but it followed me for a bit, then went airborne and whacked me in the back of the head a few times with it's wings! Woke me up, they weren't there when I went back through. I think maybe they felt trapped with the fence there so they were a little more aggressive. I also saw two snapping turtles, one of them was laying eggs right next to the path. They were sweethearts, unlike the geese!! 
The run went well, nice morning. I can still feel the birthday run in my legs and hips.
Nice morning - with Joe, Mike and Paul.
Nice run with Josh, Chris and Paul. Perfect weather!
Started with Josh K , Chris, Paul and Joe. Chris and I dropped down to the canal to add on. Saw a few snapping turtles preparing to lay their eggs and a very friendly family of geese.
Met up with Tom, Joe and Paul. Legs worked okay, thought they would be sore, but I felt pretty good. Nice to have a group to run with!!

column3: Nice Thursday Morning with Paul and Joe

column5: Paul did the first 8 with us, Joe and I added on the Tim Kane Loop to get to 20. Nice climbs on this route. We even got to see my favorite Mashaw TWICE!!!!! Jeri was out on her run. She stole Joe's car, so I gave him a ride home.

Chris needed a few roads checked off from his list. This was  a Hilly route, but very enjoyable! Pretty large group. Joe, Chris, Josh K , Kevin and Nate. Mike W. Did the first part and last, he did a workout while we were in the hills.
Another Hilly one, really enjoyed the conversations with Mike. Felt pretty good overall.
Dan Stedman met up with Paul, Joe and I for the first 8. Joe and I went on to 20. Hit some good hills. Thanks [strava://athletes/41830115/14]Daniel Stedman, it was great to catch up!!
Much cooler today!

Missed Patriot Run this morning, a deer decided to jump out in front of my wife this morning. I had to take care of her, so I missed the race. I decided to "race" since I was kinda ready for it anyway. I tried to put in the same effort as the race, happy with the results. I just feel bad letting the team down since this was an age graded cup team race. 
My wife is all good, no injuries at all.

Another good one. Jake joined us this morning which was nice, and made the pace faster. Paul was with us for the first 8, Joe, Jake and I added on. Got to see my favorite Mashaw ([strava://athletes/30371999/19]Jeri Mouse Mashaw ) at the end and had a nice conversation. She's my favorite because she doesn't make me run hills like the other Mashaw does.

Huge group of runners for this!! Probably more than some of the local races. Great to see everyone out there, it was nice to beat the heatwave that's coming next week. Thanks to the organizers [strava://athletes/29197135/21]Joe Pill Man Mashaw and [strava://athletes/30371999/19]Jeri Mouse Mashaw !  
Side note: My phone rang when I got home, it was my grandson freaking out that he caught the biggest catfish in my pond. Needed help getting it out and removing the hook. It was pretty big!!
Met up with Chris for the first 16. It was nice to stay on the flat canal path. My legs were feeling a little beat up. This felt good.
Pretty warm ! Enjoyed it though, mixed in some walking and enjoyed the conversations!
First 8 with Paul, pounded some Gatorade. Joe, Jake and I continued on. Luckily we had two places to stop for water.

column3: 10 with Paul and Tim- with a little urban running
column5: Good to run with Tim again. We got to the canal and the deer flies were pretty bad, so we went through Utica. Nice change of scenery.

This track is very nice. Paul and I met at West Canada School, but the track is under construction, so we moved it to Poland. 800's were ~2:48-2:51. Felt pretty good, but it was definitely warm. Good prep for Boilermaker in 3 weeks.
First 8 with Joe, Paul and I added on. Rain felt good toward the end.

column3: Track with Joe, Mike, Dan and Paul
column5: 3 sets of 2x400, 1x800 and 3 200's to finish. Nice and cool this morning, workout felt really controlled.

First 10 with  Craig, Mike, Paul and Tim. Craig, Mike and I added on an out/back on the canal path. Rained pretty hard the first 10 miles, sun started coming through during the second half. Garmin seems to be happy with my endurance, hopefully I can keep it there until September.
Didn't feel the best for this. I had a fever last night and slept most of the day yesterday and today. Felt okay running once I got going. Progression the last 7 miles.

column3: Track with Joe, Dan, Ryan and Mike
column5: 3 sets of 2x400 and 1x800.
First 8 with Paul and Craig. Craig and I added on. Saw an eagle perched in a tree in the marsh. Pretty warm, but it was overcast, so no direct sunlight which was kinda nice.

column3: Short one with Paul and Joe
column5: Good to get in a few Tuesday miles since I'll have to miss the Little Falls Tuesday run this week!
Nice to meet up with Paul, Joe and Mike for a few toasty miles. Felt good for this, but it was definitely warm and humid! Boilermaker might be a tough one if this is the weather we end up with!!!
Great to see everyone today!

Happy with this, someone planted the sub-60@60 seed several years ago. It didn't seem likely at the time, glad to have this behind me!! So wonderful to see so many friends today, congratulations to all!!
Still feeling a bit of Boilermaker in my legs, but cooler temps were nice.
First 10 with Paul and Mike. I shouldn't have gone 20 with the 5k tomorrow, hopefully it works out. It's always a challenge working in long runs during race weeks.
Such a great bunch of runners! 4th OA. This is a great race, great to see everyone!

column3: Little Falls Tuesday - St Johnsville Style. Boston is open to submit qualifying times.
column5: Anyone planning on running Boston, you can use your Athletes Village Account to submit your qualifying race for verification. Registration is not open yet, but they verify your time.

First 8 with Paul, Craig and I added on. Legs didn't feel great, a little sore and tired, not sure why. It was a beautiful morning, there was a little breeze and we got a couple of very short showers.
I shouldn't have done back to back 20's with Escarpment on Sunday, but it's too late now. Good excuse to take it easy at Escarpment.

Other than feeling very clumsy and trying to stay upright, this went well. I just can't charge down the rocky/rooty trails like I used to. When I picked up the pace, I'd take a fall, so I ran pretty carefully- and still fell a lot!! It was a blast!!!  Photo credit goes to [strava://athletes/53484175/13]Alison Heaphy for the photo of Dick Vincent (Race creator and race director) and I shaking hands post-race.
Working out the soreness. Nice run tonight with a great group!
Still feeling Escarpment in my quads, feeling better but not 100%.
Fun race, my brother Dan was back visiting from Kansas and jumped in!
First 8 with Paul, Joe, Mike and Craig. Added on with Mike and Craig. Felt pretty good considering the 5k was last night.
This was uncomfortable, thick smoke from the wildfires the first 10. Joe and I dropped down for the add on and it was much better. Garmin says I'm overreaching, day off tomorrow!
Some trails and a bunch of hills. A little fast work on the downs, a little bit of everything. A lot of fun..
First 8 with Paul and Joe. Really felt good to have a cool morning to run.
It was raining hard when we started, but let up for most of the first 8 with Paul. Steady rain for most of the last 12 miles, but not a heavy downpour. Glad to get it done!
Paul was planning on some 200's on the track, so we did them together. I added on from there, planned on 20, but it was a nice morning so I added on a little more.

Met up with Craig in Little Falls for this. Glad to get this week in the books, I always feel like this is the biggest week of the training cycle, good feeling. Sydney is 5 weeks out, that doesn't seem possible. I feel good for having done 6 20's in the past 9 days, hopefully a good sign. Also, I received the Boilermaker Age Group award in the mail the other day which was nice!!
Huge group tonight, Geez fed us melon and watermelon  post-run!! It hit the spot!!
Lost a couple of miles because someone forgot to start their watch.
Walker Road loop with Paul, Craig and I added on from there. Somehow I caught my toe on a loose piece of blacktop in SUNY and went down like a sack of potatoes. No harm done, but I felt foolish.
Probably the longest run before Sydney, time to start pulling back a bit. Felt pretty good today.

25th 20+ of this training block, feeling grateful for all of the friends to share miles with. Paul, Joe and I started together. Joe added on for 22 on a very hilly route. Thanks everyone for the runs!! It's been enjoyable!
Nice morning to do a nice easy 10. Met up with Tim and Josh- very enjoyable!!

column3: Canal Miles- with Josh, Nate and Chris
column5: Lots of story telling and laughs with this group! Great to get together!!

column3: Good Luck Lake Canoe with Myka and Tyson
column5: The dogs love going in the canoe. I hope we get in a few more trips this fall. The leaves are changing up there, some pretty red and orange.
10 runners showed up for this!! Great scenic run. Hit a bunch of seasonal roads.

This was a fun race, last tune up race for me. Felt pretty good overall. Didn't run my guts out because the marathon is 2 weeks out, but I did work hard for sure. 11th overall, 1st Age Group. Great to see everyone out there!
Nice hilly run with a great group this morning. Swung by the cars a few times, everyone ran a different distance, so it worked out well.
Nice to get this one in, nice cool morning for a workout. Most of these were around 37 seconds.
Nice to catch up with [strava://athletes/32985877/14]Clint Eastwood , the world traveler. It was nice of him to give me a lot of advice, and a great contact in Sydney!! Thanks!!
Another nice cool morning for a run. Met up with Tim and met Mike out on the course.

column3: Walking around Darling Harbor in Sydney, and got to the Expo. They listed the top 3 fastest marathon times in each age group for the qualifying window in 2023, my Chicago time put me in 3rd.
column5: Beth says "Hey, look over here..."

column3: Walking around and checking out the Sydney Oval start area.
column5: The parks are great, very nice city!
Met up with David for a few miles, great to catch up with him. He's going to give us a tour of Sydney this afternoon!

column3: Sydney Marathon Abbott Age Group World Championship- 102 Countries represented in the championship!
column5: Wow, tough course, very windy as well. 3rd place, so I'll get an award at the awards dinner tonight!  I didn't feel too sharp for the race, but was able to run okay. I had a little left for the finish kick which was nice. Thanks everyone for the support and miles we've shared! Incredible friends and family I have!!

The Koalas and Kangaroo were at the Toronga Zoo. The rest of the pictures were from our trip to the Blue Mountains. The Three Sisters are very impressive. I really couldn't capture the beauty in the photos, it's incredibly beautiful, breathtaking!
Nice place to work the marathon out of the legs!

column3: Manly Beach to Spit Bridge Coastal Walk

column5: We saw that there was a town called "Putney" along the Sydney Harbor so we took the ferry up to check out Putney Park and the town. It was pretty cool, and apparently has an interesting history.

column3: Watson's Bay and The Gap to Bondi Beach
column5: Really nice walk down the coastline. Whale watching from the cliffs. There were a few whales looking like they were playing, rolling on their backs. It was fun to see.

column3: Back to the North Sydney Oval
column5: I jogged up to the Oval (where the marathon started). There was a 5k fun run getting started, they do three loops. I ran one of the loops. Impressive, I bet there were at least 1,000 people running it. People in general are in really good shape here!!

column3: More sightseeing - Sydney Harbor Bridge Pylon climb, and Museum
column5: Nice stroll this morning. The more I learn about the Sydney Harbor Bridge, the more amazing it is. Built in the 1920's with no hydraulic equipment, no computers and basically no safety equipment- incredible. It was the largest steel structure in the world at the time.
We took a ride up to the northern beaches. Very nice! We saw a group of dolphins from the cliffs. A little too far away to get a photo or video.

column3: Little Falls Tuesday - Good to be back home!
column5: Just got the Boston acceptance confirmation.
Nice to catch up with Joe before they take off! Best of luck to the Berlin runners!!

column3: SUNY XC Trails with Paul and Chris
column5: Beautiful morning to run, trails were in great shape!
WOW, what perfect weather!
felt good to run a race! it's been a while, felt better than I thought I would. These races are a blast! Great to see everyone out there!
